    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-06T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-06T08:00:00-05:00" n="375"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d375">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/7982</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-06T13:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 6, 1917, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 4.58 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President’s address to Congress<note n="3" xml:id="d375fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1917#pg_IX">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1917, pp. ix</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1917#pg_XVI">xvi</ref>.</note> has been received here by the
                    whole press and public with the most enthusiastic approval and <pb facs="0529"
                        n="455" xml:id="pg_455"/> satisfaction; except the President’s speech which
                    brought us into the war, it is regarded as his most important utterance.
                    Considerable satisfaction is felt at his forecast of the possibility in certain
                    circumstances of Germany’s exclusion from the free economic intercourse which
                    must inevitably spring out of the partnership of a real peace; concerning this
                    point I sent with my despatch No. 7615 of December 3<note n="1" xml:id="d375fn1"
                        >Not printed.</note> a more important memorandum which please transmit to
                    the President as soon as received.</p>
                <p>There is also much gratification at his recommendation of war against Austria and
                    some minor regret is expressed that he did not mention also Bulgaria and
                    Turkey.</p>
                <p>The whole effect of the speech is greatly to cheer up and hearten the British and
                    to put the President still more clearly, if that were possible, as the
                    preeminent leader in the war.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
